Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey was thinking of joining the European Union, European powers were looking forward to entering its backland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, 20 steps from Asia, is one of the finest relics of its falling imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha station was designed in a neo-Renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least this is what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with observation tower in each of its angles, like some German provincial municipalities.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruin.
But once inside the woven ticket store, we have no more doubt about the size of the company, which represents a passage to the west.
The railway station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, retardating to the game of imperialism, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination through this railway that reaches Damascus, Baghdad as well as the land more known as Saudi Arabia.
But the German imperialist ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregularities.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is over.
The British and the empire forces advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there were also bad news for Hyderpasha Station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources say it is a sabotage.
Since then, it slowly falls in ruin, immersed in the memes of history.
But today, the railway passage to Anatolia and all the eastern points, serve – at least symbolically – to emphasize the expansion of the diplomatic horizons of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation of its surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new commitment policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian fractions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on a bed wagon towards the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Turkish AKP MP Suât Kiniklioglu, one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a 10 and a half-hour trip, shocked on noisy rails whose cadence reminded the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived, in the Turkish capital-presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning back to its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots, represents an example of a change in the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, and in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, expressly built in stone and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping centers and many bakery stores in which middle managers in costume-cravate- men and women- meet for morning affairs.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a center-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, cravate and he even has a Black Berry.
“The goal of this foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighborhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey was cut off from its backland.
Now she has to look to the east and west at the same time.
This was not the case of both.
She had to do both.
But now, at some point, “I asked if” Turkey shouldn’t choose?”
“Turkey,” he said, “will not have to choose between the two.”
He then emphasized an aspect that almost everyone with whom I was able to speak told me by heart: the Turkish railway goes not only to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and around the Black Sea, therefore, it is both a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
With Turkey’s integration, the message seems to draw a Europe traveling metaphorically on rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back to the Hydarpasha station, after another night without sleep, I thought again of these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
While I was waiting for the terminal, the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the period during which Turkey had been named "the sick of Europe".
