The Bee Car to Avoid Collisions
To advance the development of accidents prevention technologies, Nissan has inspired itself, this time, from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. have built this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Research in Advanced Sciences and Technologies of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow the brand vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal space of an oval shape that resembles Nissan’s security shield.
But the most important is the composed eyes of the bee, capable of seeing in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To re-create this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser range locator (Laser Range Finder).
This detects the obstacles that are on a distance of two meters and in a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
“When it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bees and immediately change direction by bifurcing its wheels of 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The greatest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is completely instinctive.
If that was the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Migration Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bees, the robot can not be turned up or down, nor in diagonal; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like the bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
“Every second this device must only process information and act according to these data.
It doesn’t need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuver, that’s why it can work continuously with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we’re not talking about memory gigabytes or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new technology for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced in serial cars in a decade according to Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a satellite GPS navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
