Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refund the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it was the third one to vote for a new Constitution.
The mission was accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" at the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the output of the voting offices and a count of a non-governmental organization announced a wide victory of the "yes", which was between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution has triumphed dramatically," he said, congratulating the Equatorians at the headquarters of the Governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was welcomed by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place quietly according to the Observatory Mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution dedicates the power of the state to the economy, reserving to it the “development planning” of a country living essentially from the oil extraction by foreign companies and the currencies that its immigrants send.
Leading by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to perform up to two consecutive four-year mandates and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and break a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of the free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty threshold.
It finally provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as the starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
