A Rabbit in the Chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his medication purchases.
Information protection experts are afraid that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There are data protection programs that link the use of the information regarding the prescription of medicines, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s to trust his chicken to a wolf,” said Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions of drugs, to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insured in case of damage depend on the customer’s health status, and if they consider that the risk is too high, they don’t even guarantee it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after getting aware of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with the pharmacies, the data about the person’s medication purchases in the last eighteen months. From this, the program determines himself, what disease the person suffers and what is his health.
For example, if this person regularly purchases high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to do to the insurer except the paperwork. However, small problems can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat burns, but they can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurance companies as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in research and data analysis. They, they have to ask for authorization from the patient before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are bound by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their faults in the past.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory analyses, and linking them to the data about the drug consumption.
More and more companies have access to data, and the control of use is getting more and more difficult.
There is a distinct law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the expansion of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specializing in data provision is currently facing Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that’s why he has developed even further his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive consent of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus and in the end, chickens depend on the kindness of the wolf.
