Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying into the desert of Nevada, was found.
The remains were found on a plateau at a height of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, at the border between California and Nevada.
But in the aircraft there is no human remains.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, eliminated the remaining doubts: "The plane was localized, we sent a team, and now we have the confirmation that it is the one on which Steve Fosset was traveling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found either on the plane or in the surrounding area.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transport Safety Bureau (Ntsb) that a team of investigators sent to the site, a few hours after the detection of the accident, identified the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset landed from Yerington to Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal effects of Fosset were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a pull.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
